<p>Naive Rationality has classic failure modes.</p>

<ol>
  <li>Failing to take into account 2nd and 3rd effects
  This often happens when those 2nd and 3rd effects are unknown to rationality but known to intuition</li>
  <li>Long Term Thinking
  Naive rationality leads to undervaluing poorly understood activity, (ex. Play / exploration) for maximizing expected value greedily in each moment</li>
  <li>Lack of Complex Consequentialism
  â€˜Consistencyâ€™ demands that we choose either Deontology or Consequentialism, or some other framework for evaluating actions. But these systems all have value in particular contexts, and so should subsume one another. For example, effective rules often have to be clear (discrete) for psychological reasons, which leads to Deontology. The consequentialist should realize when that optimizes the outcome.</li>
  <li>Disrespect for Intuition / Cultural Knowledge
  What people mean when they say â€˜wisdomâ€™ is knowledge whose source is unknown, unknowable or forgotten. Passed from generations of Elders. Intuited through a distributed, parallel process in a mind that canâ€™t be understood linearly.</li>
  <li>Rational People Defect and Free Ride
  There are many game-theoretic situations where cooperation is only enforced by social norms. In that context, a person relying on rationality instead of social imitation will defect (assuming that the long term ramifications for reputation, etc. are low)</li>
  <li>Assuming Normal Distributions in Extremistan</li>
  <li>What you see is all there is (relevant to Chestertonâ€™s fence)</li>
  <li>Believing that youâ€™re rational leads to being overconfident in your understanding of the situation</li>
  <li>Ignore the emotional side of thought / experience
